=Mountains=

==List of famous mountains 名山 in China==
* 五嶽: 泰山(東嶽), 衡山 (南嶽), 華山 (西嶽), 恆山 (北嶽), 嵩山 (中嶽)
* 三山五嶽
* 四大佛教名山
* Emei Shan 峨眉山
* Luofu Shan 羅浮山

==List of less famous mountains==
* Wangwu Shan 王屋山, Nüji Shan 女几山, Lu Shan 廬山

==List of mountains in other asian countries==
* 台灣五岳
* 韓國五嶽: 동악 東嶽 - 금강산 金剛山, 서악 西嶽 - 묘향산 妙香山, 남악 南嶽 - 지리산 智異山, 북악 北嶽 - 백두산 白頭山, 중악 中嶽 - 삼각산 北漢山



==Literature==
===Monographs===
* Karl Johaentges, Uli Franz: Chinas Heilige Berge. München: Frederking & Thaler, 2005.
* Joan Qionglin Tan: Han Shan, Chan Buddhism and Gary Snyder's Ecopoetic Way, Sussex: Sussex Academic Press, 2009.
* Édouard Chavannes: Le T'ai chan. Essai de monographie d'un culte chinois. Appendice Le dieu du sol dans la Chine antique. Paris: Ernest Leroux, 1910. [[@http://classiques.uqac.ca/classiques/chavannes_edouard/C06_le_tai_chan/tai_chan.pdf|PDF]] 
* James Morris Hargett: Stairway to heaven: a journey to the summit of Mount Emei. New York: SUNY Press, 2008.
* Robert E. Harrist: The Landscape of Words. Stone Inscriptions from Early and Medieval China.  University of Washington Press, 2008
* Wolfram Eberhard: Hua Shan - the Taoist sacred mountain in west China ; its scenery, monasteries, and monks. Hong Kong: Vetch and Lee, 1974
* Susan Naquin and Chün-fang Yü: Pilgrims and sacred sites in China. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1992
===PhD Dissertations===
* Thomas H. Hahn: Formalisierter Wilder Raum - Chinesische Berge und ihre Beschreibungen (shanzhi). Dissertation, Heidelberg 1996. [[@http://archiv.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/volltextserver/volltexte/2007/7287/|PDF]] 
===Articles===
* Zhang Yushu: Die Benennung der Berge in China. In: INST Institut zur Erforschung und Förderung regionaler und transnationaler Kulturprozesse (Hrsg.): Die Namen Der Berge. [[@http://www.inst.at/berge/perspektiven/zhang.htm|Link]] 
* Robert E. Harrist: "Writing, Landscape, and Representation in Sixth-Century China: Reading Cloud Peak Mountain. [雲峰山]", Between Han and Tang - Visual and Material Culture in a Transformative Period. Beijing: Wenwu Chubanshe, 2003.
* Thomas Hahn: The Standard Taoist Mountain and Related Features of Religious Geography. Cahiers d'Extrême-Asie, Vol. 4 No. 4 (1988): pp. 145-156. [[@http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/asie_0766-1177_1988_num_4_1_916|PDF]] 
* Glen Dubridge: Women Pilgrims to T'ai Shan: Some Pages from a Seventeenth Century Novel. In Susan Naquin and Chün-fang Yü: Pilgrims and sacred sites in China. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1992: 39-64
* Pei-Yi Wu: An Ambivalent Pilgrim to T'ai Shan in the Seventeenth Century. In Susan Naquin and Chün-fang Yü: Pilgrims and sacred sites in China. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1992: 65-88
* Shawn Eichmann: Illustration of the True Forms of the Five Sacred Peaks (Cat. No. 137). In Stephen Little: Taoism and the Arts of China. Chicago: The Art Institute of Chicago, 2000: 358-359
* Sandrine Chenivesse: A  Journey to the Depths of A Labyrinth-Landscape: The Mount Fengdu [鄷都山], Taoist Holy Site and Infernal Abyss. In A. W. Macdonald (ed.): Mandala and Landscape. New Delhi: Printworld, 1997: 41-74.
===Talks===
*  Yu Myŏngin 柳明仁: "The Success Story of the Diamond Mountains: A Reflection on the Genesis of the Sacred Site and the Contemporary Discourses on the Buddhicization of the Korean Landscape". The 5th World Congress of Korean Studies, Chinese Culture University, Taipei, 26-27 October 2010. » [[@http://www.ruhr-uni-bochum.de/skk/yu/yu_talk_20101027.pdf|abstract]] 

==Quotations==
* "Xie Lingyun [[謝靈運]] (385-433) in one of his eulogies compares the beneficial influence of Huiyuan’s monastery on Mt. Lu to that of the “Vulture Peak” near Rajagrha where many sutras are said to have been spoken by the Buddha. In fact, several mountains all over China have been called Lingjiu Shan 靈鷲山 [[@http://www.zdic.net/cd/ci/7/ZdicE7Zdic81ZdicB5266159.htm|Zdic]], the traditional translation of Grdhrakuta one of these is already attested at the beginning of the fifth century." (Zürcher 1959, 207-208)